<TITLE> Dhaka stocks edge down </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, March 31 (bdnews24.com)Dhaka stocks ended slightly lower Monday as investors sold in power and cement with an eye on profit-taking. "Investors sold off power and cement shares throughout the day to lock in their profits, while continuing to buy in banks and mutual funds," an official of IDLC told bdnews24.com. Dhaka Stock Exchange chief executive Salahuddin Ahmed said the decline was not significant as the sell-off was limited to particular sectors. The market kicked off with a slight rise, fluctuated throughout the day, before dipping again toward the close to end lower. The benchmark DGEN or general index fell 5.19 points, or 0.17 percent, to end on 3016.48. The DSI or all-share price index finished at 2547.34, down 4.53 points, or 0.17 percent. The bourse's blue-chip DSE-20 lost 24.17 points, or 1.03 percent, to close at 2317.33. Turnover on the country's prime bourse amounted to Tk 3.04 billion from 18,420,783 traded shares. Losers outnumbered winners 191 to 63, with only one issue remaining unchanged. The day's trading saw the share prices of banks and mutual funds rise, while power and cement shares fell on profit taking. Pharmaceuticals closed mixed. AB Bank topped the turnover board, rising 3.39 percent to end on Tk 3477.50. Square Pharma followed, ending on Tk 4110.25, up 0.48 percent. Power Grid Company of Bangladesh declined following a period of gains, ending 3.72 percent lower at Tk 666.25. Lanka Bangla Finance rose 8.04 percent to end on Tk 107.40, while Uttara Bank continued its advance to close at Tk 5461.25, up 2.22 percent. Among other scrips on the turnover board: Beximco Pharma, Heidelberg Cement and DESCO fell. Lafarge Surma Cement and IFIC Bank rose. Indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange closed mixed, with a significant rise in turnover being registered. Turnover on the port city's bourse surged to Tk 651.65 million from Tk 216.14 million the previous day, from 5,701,621 traded shares. The CSCX or selective categories index ended on 5380.16, up 21 points, or 0.39 percent. The CASPI or all-share price index rose 27.01 points, or 0.32 percent, to finish at 8329.01. The CSE-30 blue-chip fell 13.25 points, or 0.18 percent, to close at 7120.05. bdn
